[2] Shigellosis - Viet Nam
Date: Mon 22 Mar 2010
From: Stephen Baker <sbaker@oucru.org> [edited]


At the Hospital for Tropical Diseases in Ho Chi Minh City (HCMC),
Viet Nam, shigella is the leading bacterial cause of children
hospitalized with diarrhea. We have performed a number of treatment
and observational studies looking at dysentery and particularly
shigellosis.

Interestingly, over a 15 year period we also have seen a change in
the dominant species but the inverse of the observations reported
from Toronto (ProMED-mail Shigellosis, changing epidemiology -
Canada: (ON) RFI 20100216.0548). We have seen a progressive species
shift from _S. flexneri_ to _S. sonnei_ (Vinh et al: A changing
picture of shigellosis in southern Vietnam: shifting species
dominance, antimicrobial susceptibility and clinical presentation.
BMC Infectious Diseases 2009, 9:204; [available at
<http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2334/9/204>]). In fact, in
2009/2010 more than 95 percent of isolates are multiple drug
resistant _S. sonnei_ that are also resistant to 3rd generation
cephalosporins [such as ceftriaxone - Mod.LL] and demonstrate reduced
susceptibility to fluoroquinolones [such as ciprofloxacin. - Mod.LL]

The dominant shigella species may be dependent on the location and
stage of economic development. _S. sonnei_ appear to be most commonly
associated with industrialized countries while _S. flexneri_ is
associated with less industrialized countries. Fluctuations in the
incidence of _S. flexneri_ serotypes within a single location have
also been recorded and because immunity to secondary shigella
infections is believed to be serotype specific, this may be the
driving force. The reason for the change in shigellosis species in a
specific location is unknown and may be due to number of factors
involved in the transmission, environmental niche, the infectious
dose and also the changing economic conditions. Immunity (or the lack
of) possibly caused by exposure (or none exposure) to unrelated
organisms with a similar LPS antigen may change the selective
pressure on the organisms. We do not currently understand the driving
forces behind the change in HCMC, if there is clonal expansion of one
particular dominant strain with increased fitness and ability to out
compete other serotypes or whether there are other secondary
contributing factors in a community going through profound economic
and social change. We are currently investigating this in HCMC.

Because there is less shigellosis in places such as Canada,
transmission of the bacteria and population immunity is also more
limited. It is possible that the change in species that has been
observed in Toronto is related to a specific dominant strain that has
been introduced via international travel. Shigellosis is a common
imported infection from parts of Asia and men who have sex with men
(MSM) may be a transmission route of a dominant strain. Contact and
social network analysis with serotyping and genotyping would be
useful to distinguish if multiple strains or an individual _S.
flexneri_ clone is circulating. The main reservoir may be MSM, which
may lead to community infections in the population through the
individual shedding organisms. Global mapping data of this serotypic
and genotypic data would be useful to trace the primary sources of
infection and lead to a greater understanding of the changing
patterns of shigellosis in rapidly changing countries like Viet Nam
and where the disease emerges as recently described in Canada.

---
Dr Stephen Baker
Dr Ha Vinh
Professor Jeremy Farrar
Oxford University Clinical Research Unit
The Hospital for Tropical Diseases
Ho Chi Minh City, Viet Nam
<sbaker@oucru.org>

[Ho Chi Minh City can be located via the HealthMap/ProMED-mail
interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/01ba>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

